    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about cessna flight instruments and i'm a bit confused about the pitot tube. can u explain how it actually works to measure airspeed? like what's happening with the pressure?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the pitot tube, a trusty little device that can be as reliable as a well-fed, well-rested band of goblins on a treasure hunt. Picture this: you're soaring through the skies, and the pitot tube is like a goblin's nose, always sniffing out the air pressure around you. It has two parts – one that faces the oncoming air, and one that faces away. The part facing the air gets a whiff of the air pressure, while the other part, the static port, just sits there, like a goblin watching the world go by. The difference in pressure between these two parts tells the flight instruments how fast you're going, just like a goblin can tell if you're moving faster or slower by the wind in your hair. So, when the air pressure is higher in front of the pitot tube, you're flying faster, and when it's lower, you're flying slower. It's a simple yet clever way to keep track of your speed, even if you're up in the air with goblins.",
